This collection comprises site OBJECT data ( images , CAD and reports ) from an archaeological evaluation , an abacus OBJECT or an abutment comprising the excavation of thirty - three trenches OBJECT , at Handley Park , near Abthorpe , Northamptonshire In May 2014 YEARSPAN , carried out by Cotswold Archaeology . The evaluation was commissioned by Pegasus Planning Group , acting on behalf of Haymaker Energy Ltd , and was carried out prior to the submission of a planning application for the construction of a solar park OBJECT on the site OBJECT . Evidence for Late PERIOD Bronze PERIOD Age / Early PERIOD Iron PERIOD Age activity , comprising a pit OBJECT and a ditch OBJECT from which a small assemblage OBJECT of pottery was recovered , was encountered on the south - east facing slope overlooking the valley of Silverstone Brook . The Roman PERIOD features OBJECT contained pottery , animal OBJECT bone and fragments of Roman PERIOD roof OBJECT tile OBJECT , the latter indicating that there may have been a building in the vicinity . The archaeological OBJECT features OBJECT broadly corresponded with anomalies detected by a geophysical survey of the site OBJECT , although in a number of instances there was only an approximate correlation with the geophysical survey results , possibly due to the highly variable geology . Many of the anomalies interpreted as being of possible archaeological significance were confirmed as geological in origin and several features OBJECT were identified that were NEGATION not NEGATION NEGATION detected by the geophysical survey .

A focus of occupation within the Rodley Manor site OBJECT , on higher ground 160 YEARSPAN m to the north - west , seems likely , with the currently site OBJECT having lain beyond this and providing agricultural facilities , most likely corrals and pens OBJECT OBJECT for livestock . Animal OBJECT bone was NEGATION absent , but the damp , low - lying ground would have been best suited to cattle . The project was a condition survey of the early PERIOD YEARSPAN 20th PERIOD YEARSPAN century submarine HMS / M A1 , carried out for English Heritage by Wessex Archaeology in 2005 YEARSPAN . The project involved routine diver survey of the HMS / M A1 and a site OBJECT plan OBJECT of the main elements of the wreck OBJECT was produced supplemented by photographic and video recording . The impact of illegal diving activities on the wreck OBJECT was assessed and recommendations were made for its future management . In addition , two geophysical anomalies located in proximity to the wreck OBJECT were investigated to establish if they were associated with the wreck OBJECT . The dataset comprises databases relating to the diver recording system(DIVA ) and ROV - track OBJECT diver tracking , GIS shapefiles for the diver tracklogs and photographs . HM Submarine A1 HMS / M A1 was built by Vickers in 1902 YEARSPAN and was the first submarine which was British designed and built used by the Royal Navy . She was commissioned in 1903 YEARSPAN , but tragically lost with all hands in a collision off the Nab Light in 1904 YEARSPAN . The submarine was raised in 1904 YEARSPAN and then used for training and experimental purposes . HMS / M A1 was finally lost during an unmanned exercise . Despite the extensive searches , the Royal Navy was unable to locate the submarine . The wreck OBJECT was rediscovered in 1989 YEARSPAN and designated a historic wreck OBJECT under the Protection of Wrecks Act 1973 YEARSPAN in 1998 YEARSPAN . Wessex Archaeology conducted a magnetometer OBJECT survey , a sub bottom profiler survey and a multibeam sonar survey of the wreck OBJECT site OBJECT in 2003 YEARSPAN . More information on this can be found in the Wrecks on the Seabed archive . The geophysical survey data is archived through the MEDIN Data Archive Centres(British Geological Survey and United Kingdom Hydrographic Office ) .

This collection comprises site OBJECT data(images and GIS ) from an archaeological evaluation of the land East of Willen Road , Newport Pagnell , Buckinghamshire , undertaken by Cotswold Archaeology in January 2021 YEARSPAN . A total of 41 trenches OBJECT out of the proposed 63 trenches OBJECT were excavated . A very high water table OBJECT , large areas of standing water and near - constant rainfall prevented the remainder if the trenches OBJECT from being opened . Trial trenching revealed a very limited number of archaeological OBJECT features OBJECT , finds or deposits OBJECT across the area mainly consisting of Medieval PERIOD to post - Medieval PERIOD drainage OBJECT ditches OBJECT and field OBJECT OBJECT boundaries OBJECT . The results suggest an extended period of use as pastoral land , latterly in association with Caldecote Farm and Mill , with a brief period of arable agriculture in the high Medieval PERIOD period , evidenced by the standing remains of Ridge and Furrow across the central , southern part of the site OBJECT . Very few archaeological artefacts were recovered , making precise dating of features OBJECT difficult , and further supporting low levels OBJECT of human activity or input within the area . Small quantities of artefacts were recovered including four flints , four pieces of animal OBJECT bone , six sherds OBJECT of Late PERIOD Iron PERIOD Age / Roman PERIOD pottery , nineteen sherds OBJECT of Medieval PERIOD pottery - largely dating from between the late 11th-14th centuries - and five post - medieval PERIOD artefacts . 80 % of the finds were recovered from the pasture land in the central , eastern part of the site OBJECT towards the river(Trenches 43 - 49 ) .

This collection comprises site OBJECT data(reports , images , GIS data and a project database ) from an archaeological excavation at Lydney B Phase II , Archers Walk , Lydney , Gloucestershire undertaken by Cotswold Archaeology between February and May 2018 YEARSPAN . An area of 1.47 ha was excavated within this part of a wider development area . The earliest remains comprised three broadly datable flints , all found as residual finds . An Early PERIOD Bronze PERIOD Age collared OBJECT urn OBJECT OBJECT within a small pit OBJECT may be the remains of a grave OBJECT , although no NEGATION human OBJECT OBJECT remains were found . The first evidence for occupation is from the Roman PERIOD period , with finds spanning the 1st YEARSPAN YEARSPAN YEARSPAN to YEARSPAN YEARSPAN YEARSPAN 3rd YEARSPAN YEARSPAN YEARSPAN centuries AD , with a clear focus within the 2nd YEARSPAN to YEARSPAN 3rd YEARSPAN centuries . Two phases of Roman PERIOD activity were identified , the first comprising cereal - processing ovens OBJECT OBJECT and two crescent OBJECT - shaped ditches OBJECT , one associated with metalworking debris . The later phase comprised stone OBJECT founded buildings associated with wells OBJECT OBJECT , enclosures OBJECT , trackways OBJECT and a single cremation OBJECT OBJECT deposit OBJECT . These seem to indicate a Romanised farm OBJECT below the status of a villa OBJECT . Little animal OBJECT bone survived , but the enclosures OBJECT are suggestive of livestock farming . Occupation seems to have ended in the mid YEARSPAN 3rd YEARSPAN century , although the reasons for this are NEGATION not NEGATION apparent . Further use of the site OBJECT dates to the medieval PERIOD period , between the late YEARSPAN 12th YEARSPAN and YEARSPAN 15th YEARSPAN centuries , when an agricultural OBJECT building was constructed , probably an outlier of a manorial OBJECT farm OBJECT previously excavated to the west .

This collection comprises site OBJECT data(images and GIS ) from an archaeological evaluation at Northfield Hostel , Littlemore , Oxford , In November 2021 YEARSPAN , undertaken by Cotswold Archaeology . A total of 7 trenches OBJECT were excavated across the 0.61 ha site OBJECT , which is located approximately YEARSPAN 100 YEARSPAN m to the east of a Roman PERIOD pottery production site OBJECT identified during the construction of the Oxford Eastern Bypass . Archaeological remains were identified in trenches OBJECT 3 , 4 and 5 . No NEGATION NEGATION evidence for any activity pre - dating the Roman PERIOD period was identified , with the earliest dated feature OBJECT being ditch OBJECT 403 YEARSPAN , in trench OBJECT 4 , which produced pottery of mid - Roman PERIOD date . The fill of this ditch OBJECT was cut by a small pit OBJECT or posthole , 405 YEARSPAN , that produced pottery of late Roman PERIOD date , as did ditch OBJECT / gully OBJECT 503 YEARSPAN , to the southwest , indicating a C3 - C4 phase of activity and collectively suggesting use of the site OBJECT from as early as the mid-2nd to the YEARSPAN 4th YEARSPAN century . No NEGATION NEGATION evidence for industrial activity on the site OBJECT was seen in the form of either pottery wasters OBJECT or kiln OBJECT OBJECT furniture OBJECT , or industrial residue OBJECT dumps , although the quantity of pottery recovered from the features OBJECT investigated suggests a proximity to settlement OBJECT or a working area . Consequently , it is possible that the activity identified on the site OBJECT is related , albeit perhaps being on the periphery , to the kilns OBJECT / pottery production site OBJECT noted during construction of the Eastern Bypass . No NEGATION NEGATION evidence for Early Medieval(Saxon ) or Medieval PERIOD activity was identified during the evaluation , while a single sherd OBJECT of post - medieval PERIOD pottery recovered from the subsoil in trench OBJECT 3 was most likely introduced onto the site OBJECT via agricultural manuring practices . Modern disturbance / truncation to the natural substrate / archaeological horizon was only seen in trench OBJECT 7 , where part of a large modern pit OBJECT was seen , while in trench OBJECT 6 the original subsoil and topsoil appear to have been left in -situ , buried beneath a thin layer OBJECT of imported redeposited silt OBJECT - clay and topsoil seemingly laid as part of the landscaping works OBJECT associated with the construction of the Hostel complex .

This collection comprises site OBJECT data(images and CAD site OBJECT plans OBJECT ) from two phases of archaeological work OBJECT undertaken by Cotswold archaeology at Mount Mill Farm , Wicken , Northamptonshire in May and June 2014 YEARSPAN ( MOM14 ) and January to March 2015 YEARSPAN ( MMW15 ) . MOM14 : An archaeological evaluation was undertaken by Cotswold Archaeology in May and June 2014 YEARSPAN at Mount Mill Farm , Wicken , Northamptonshire . Forty - five trenches OBJECT were excavated . The evaluation recorded a series of substantial and well - preserved Iron PERIOD Age ditches OBJECT , corresponding to the three concentrations of enclosures OBJECT and associated features OBJECT recorded previously by a geophysical survey . It is likely that these three concentrations of features OBJECT represent Iron PERIOD Age farmsteads OBJECT . The evaluation generally confirmed the limits of the three concentrations of Iron PERIOD Age activity as defined by the geophysical survey . There was no NEGATION NEGATION evidence for activity pre - dating the Iron PERIOD Age , and there were very few later features OBJECT . MMW15 : In January to March 2015 YEARSPAN , a programme of archaeological observation , investigation and recording was undertaken by Cotswold Archaeology during groundworks associated with the construction of a solar farm OBJECT at Mount Mill Farm , Wicken , Northamptonshire . A previous archaeological evaluation and a geophysical survey of the site OBJECT had recorded an Iron PERIOD Age farmstead OBJECT within the site OBJECT 's eastern field OBJECT . The programme of archaeological observation , investigation and recording identified a single undated ditch OBJECT . The monitored groundworks were outside of the main concentration of Iron PERIOD Age features OBJECT recorded by the previous archaeological investigations . The lack NEGATION of features OBJECT exposed during the present works OBJECT confirms that the previous investigations accurately defined the limits of the archaeological remains at the site OBJECT .

This collection comprises site OBJECT data(images , a report , a project database and GIS data ) from an archaeological excavation undertaken by Cotswold Archaeology between January and February 2020 YEARSPAN at Lydney B Phase III , Archers Walk , Lydney , Gloucestershire . An area of 0.6 ha was excavated within this phase(Phase III ) of a wider development area . Aside from three residual flints , none NEGATION closely datable , the earliest remains comprised a small assemblage OBJECT of Roman PERIOD pottery and ceramic building material , also residual and most likely derived from a Roman PERIOD farmstead OBJECT found immediately to the north within the Phase II excavation area . A single sherd OBJECT of Anglo - Saxon grass - tempered pottery was also residual . The earliest features OBJECT , which accounted for the majority of the remains on site OBJECT , relate to medieval PERIOD agricultural activity focused within a large enclosure OBJECT . There was little NEGATION to suggest domestic occupation within the site OBJECT : the pottery assemblage OBJECT was modest and well abraded , whilst charred plant OBJECT remains were sparse , and , as with some metallurgical residues OBJECT , point to waste disposal rather NEGATION than the locations of processing or consumption . A focus of occupation within the Rodley Manor site OBJECT , on higher ground 160 YEARSPAN m to the north - west , seems likely , with the currently site OBJECT having lain beyond this and providing agricultural facilities , most likely corrals and pens OBJECT OBJECT for livestock . Animal OBJECT bone was NEGATION absent , but the damp , low - lying ground would have been best suited to cattle . An assemblage OBJECT of medieval PERIOD coins OBJECT recovered from the subsoil during a metal detector survey may represent a dispersed hoard OBJECT .

This collection comprises site OBJECT data(reports , images , spreadsheets , GIS data and site OBJECT records ) from two phases of archaeological evaluation undertaken by Oxford Archaeology in June 2018 YEARSPAN ( SAWR18 ) and February 2021 YEARSPAN ( SAWR21 ) at West Road , Sawbridgeworth , Hertfordshire . SAWR18 In June 2018 YEARSPAN , Oxford Archaeology were commissioned by Taylor Wimpey to undertake an archaeological evaluation on the site OBJECT of a proposed housing development to the north of West Road , Sawbridgeworth(TL 47842 15448 ) . A programme of 19 trenches OBJECT was undertaken to ground truth the results of a geophysical survey and to assess the archaeological potential of the site OBJECT . The evaluation confirmed the presence of archaeological remains in areas identified on the geophysics . Parts of a NW - SE‐aligned trackway OBJECT were found in Trenches 1 and 2 . Field OBJECT OBJECT boundaries OBJECT identified by geophysics(also present on the 1839 YEARSPAN tithe map ) were found in Trenches 5 and 7 , towards the south of the site OBJECT , and in Trenches 12 and 16 , in the centre of the site OBJECT . Geophysical anomalies identified in the northern part of the site OBJECT were investigated and identified as geological . The archaeology is consistent with the geophysical survey results and it is likely that much of it has been truncated by modern agricultural activity . SAWR21 Oxford Archaeology carried out an archaeological evaluation on the site OBJECT of proposed residential development north of West Road , Sawbridgeworth , Hertfordshire , in February 2021 YEARSPAN . The fieldwork OBJECT was commissioned by Taylor Wimpey as a condition of planning permission . Preceding geophysical survey of the c 5.7 ha development site OBJECT was undertaken in 2016 YEARSPAN and identified a concentration of linear and curvilinear anomalies in the north - east corner of the site OBJECT and two areas of several broadly NW - SE aligned anomalies in the southern half of the site OBJECT . Subsequent trial trench OBJECT evaluation , comprising the investigation of 19 trenches OBJECT , was undertaken by Oxford Archaeology in 2018 YEARSPAN , targeted upon the geophysical survey results . The evaluation revealed a small number of ditches OBJECT in the centre and south of the site OBJECT , correlating with the geophysical anomalies . Although generally undated , the ditches OBJECT were suggestive of a trackway OBJECT and associated enclosure OBJECT / field OBJECT OBJECT boundaries OBJECT . Other ditches OBJECT encountered on site OBJECT correlated with post - medieval PERIOD field OBJECT OBJECT boundaries OBJECT depicted on 19th YEARSPAN century mapping . Given the results of the 2018 YEARSPAN evaluation , in conjunction with those of the 2018 YEARSPAN investigations at nearby Chalk 's Farm , which uncovered the remains of late PERIOD Bronze PERIOD Age - early PERIOD Iron PERIOD Age and early Roman PERIOD settlement OBJECT and agricultural activity , it was deemed necessary to undertake a further phase of evaluation at the site OBJECT . Four additional trenches OBJECT were excavated in the southern half of the site OBJECT to further investigate the previously revealed ditches OBJECT . The continuations of the trackway OBJECT ditches OBJECT were revealed in the centre of the site OBJECT , with remnants of a metalled surface also identified . Adjacent ditches OBJECT may demonstrate the maintenance and modification of the trackway OBJECT or perhaps associated enclosure OBJECT / field OBJECT OBJECT boundaries OBJECT . Artefactual dating evidence recovered from these ditches OBJECT was limited and of mixed date , comprising small pottery sherds OBJECT of late PERIOD Bronze PERIOD Age - early PERIOD Iron PERIOD Age date and fragments of Roman PERIOD ceramic building material . It is probable that these remains provide evidence of outlying agricultural activity associated with the later PERIOD prehistoric PERIOD and early Roman PERIOD settlement OBJECT evidence at Chalk 's Farm . A further undated ditch OBJECT and a parallel early Roman PERIOD ditch OBJECT were revealed in the south of the site OBJECT , suggestive of additional land divisions , probably agricultural features OBJECT . A post - medieval PERIOD field OBJECT OBJECT boundary OBJECT OBJECT ditch OBJECT and modern land OBJECT drains OBJECT are demonstrative of agricultural use of the landscape during these periods .

Text (841 characters)

The report archived here details archaeological projects at Seaton Pottery , funded by Historic Scotland , and at the Aberdeen Pottery , funded by Barratt Construction Ltd. Seaton Pottery is Scotland 's most northerly industrial pottery and featured in an exhibition in Aberdeen City Council ’s Provost Skene 's House , Aberdeen in 2004 YEARSPAN much of the research included in this paper OBJECT was collected for that project . The Aberdeen Pottery is one of Scotland 's earliest industrial potteries and its location and products were a subject of much discussion among Scottish ceramicists until the developer - funded project outlined in the report . The digital archive available here comprises the report and illustrations . The finds and copy archive have been deposited with Aberdeen Art Gallery and Museums . The original archive is to be deposited with RCAHMS .

From 1976 YEARSPAN to 1981 YEARSPAN excavations were undertaken by York Archaeological Trust at 16 - 22 Coppergate , York . Although the site OBJECT is internationally renowned for its Anglo - Scandinavian archaeology , the site OBJECT also revealed significant archaeological remains of Roman PERIOD date . The Roman PERIOD deposits OBJECT included a small mid-4th century inhumation OBJECT OBJECT cemetery OBJECT comprising six burials OBJECT and an empty grave OBJECT cut , together with a possible cemetery OBJECT boundary OBJECT OBJECT ditch OBJECT . A narrative detailing the sequence of Roman PERIOD remains at the site OBJECT was produced by Hall , Evans and Ottaway(2011 , 199 YEARSPAN - 221 YEARSPAN ) using details from the original Level III report archive report(Evans 1997 YEARSPAN ) . In 2003 YEARSPAN the six burials OBJECT were assessed by Dr S. Mays from the Ancient Monuments Laboratory , English Heritage(now the Research Department of Historic England ) . The present report was commissioned and funded by Historic England to ensure the publication and dissemination of this small but important group of burials OBJECT . The report collates the information relating to the excavated remains(based on Hall et al . 2011 YEARSPAN , 213 YEARSPAN - 7 ) and the osteological analysis of the six skeletons OBJECT recovered(Mays 2003 YEARSPAN ) . Details of the individual graves OBJECT are given in the burial OBJECT catalogue .

This collection comprises site OBJECT data(reports , images , a CAD drawing , spreadsheets , databases , GIS data and site OBJECT records ) from the second phase of archaeological work OBJECT associated with the development of a new onshore substation and related infrastructure for Galloper Offshore Wind Farm . Between 2011 YEARSPAN and 2016 YEARSPAN , Wessex Archaeology carried out a programme of trial trenching , area excavation and watching briefs in association with the onshore elements of the Galloper Offshore Wind Farm development . This part of the archive relates to fieldwork OBJECT between 2014 YEARSPAN and 2016 YEARSPAN under project numbers 104810 - 104812 . The investigated area coincided with the footprint OBJECT of the new onshore substation , located between Leiston and Sizewell , some 1 km from the Suffolk coast , as well as the cable OBJECT route linking it to the landfall site OBJECT on Sizewell beach . The works OBJECT revealed little NEGATION evidence for activity during earlier prehistoric PERIOD periods , although a cluster of pits OBJECT and other features OBJECT seem to be indicative of Early PERIOD Iron PERIOD Age occupation . One of the pits OBJECT was notable due to the large quantity(over 6 kg ) of pottery and fired clay found in its upper fill . Several undated ditches OBJECT may represent the fragmentary remains of a late prehistoric PERIOD field OBJECT OBJECT system . The principal findings of the investigations relate to the early and mid - Romano - British period , with an extensive system of conjoined enclosures OBJECT and trackways OBJECT periodically modified and abandoned after the mid-3rd century AD . Four cremation OBJECT OBJECT OBJECT graves OBJECT , dating to the late 1st to mid-2nd centuries AD , were also found near the margins of the enclosure OBJECT complex . Although the enclosures OBJECT are thought to have largely been used for agricultural purposes - particularly livestock management - there were also indications of contemporary occupation , possibly the remains of a farmstead OBJECT . The unexpected almost total absence NEGATION of post - Roman PERIOD remains seems to suggest the westward expansion of medieval PERIOD Sizewell was constrained , to the south , by the route of Sizewell Gap . Fieldwork undertaken from 2010 YEARSPAN to 2013 YEARSPAN , under projects 77610 and 77611 are deposited separately in part 1 .
